If you've ever used the terminal in Linux, BusyBox gives you that similar 
function by allowing your phone to do or take similar commands. Windows and 
Command Prompt? Same idea. Most cell phones are just that, a phone. They 
don't need a terminal that can take commands or a command prompt that can 
take commands. You might not need it, but the guy who gave you the custom 
Rom or root method to get you where you are now needed you to have it to 
make your root method or custom Rom flash even possible.

Unbelievable this is still updated regularly after all these years, great 
work! All those people giving bad reviews claiming this doesn't work have 
to understand the install method will vary from phone to phone - some newer 
phones especially don't seem to allow for installation to the /xbin folder, 
meaning you'll have to install to /sbin or /bin after every reboot. This is 
the way android is built now and no fault of the Busybox developer, so what 
worked on your old phone may not work now. Sheesh, you'd think people 
rooting their phones would put a little effort into understanding the 
process before down voting a fantastic developer....

I performed a smart install on an S7, followed a few hours later by a smart uninstall, and ended up with a borked system with no id command (and possibly other, less obvious side-effects). I tried to manually restore order, but to no avail. I had to restore /system from a fresh back-up to get back to where I was prior to messing with this app. I tried a few days later a second time, this time on an S6, performing a normal (non-smart) install, followed by a normal uninstall: exactly the same result, with id removed. I wrote to the developer expressing my displeasure and asking for a refund, but he did not reply.  Hazardous software and unresponsive developer. Proceed with extreme caution. A good alternative can be found in the meefik BusyBox, with simpler installation and more applets. UPDATE: I figured out that uninstalling BusyBox incorrectly creates a symlink of id to Toolbox instead of to Toybox. The Samsung Marshmallow firmware doesn't have an id applet in its Toolbox binary, so the effect is as if the id command had been removed. This can be fixed as root by remounting /system as read-write and manually symlinking id back to Toybox. After that, id works again as expected.

Application was able to cleanup multiple BusyBox installs on my OS and lay down a single version in /system/xbin. The uninstall process comes with warnings, but worked well on my stock ROM (2.2). Fast response from developer on an v.8.0 glitch.

After running, it indicated the previous version was installed in /system/xbin yet prompted to be installed in /system/bin. All hell broke loose after changing this to /system/xbin and selecting install.     Long story short....The installation failed, could not su to root anymore and no apps requiring root would work thereafter even though the SuperUser app said it was granting root permissions. Also, lost WiFi and ADB stopped working via the USB cable. Had to restore a CWM backup of /system but did another backup before restoring so as to be able to see what went wrong.    Sure enough, there is the V8.0 busybox file in /system/bin after extracting the /system archive from the latest CWM backup. In other words, it tried to install itself in /system/bin anyway and in doing so prevented access to /system/bin thereafter for some strange reason.
